var definitions = ['<h2>Vielleicht kann ich dein Auto reparieren.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "perhaps" or "maybe". It indicates the possibility or likelihood of an action or event.</div><div><strong>kann</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense conjugation of the verb "können", which means "can" or "to be able to". It shows the speaker’s ability to perform an action.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>dein</strong> This is the informal, singular, possessive pronoun in the accusative case in German, meaning "your". It denotes ownership or association with the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>Auto</strong> This noun means "car" in English. In the sentence, it’s the direct object being potentially acted upon by the verb (reparieren).</div><div><strong>reparieren</strong> This is the infinitive form of a verb in German, meaning "to repair". In this sentence, it indicates the action that the speaker might perform on the car.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht sind Sie erkältet.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "maybe" or "perhaps". It indicates that what follows is a possibility or a suggestion rather than a certainty.</div><div><strong>sind</strong> This is the second-person formal or third-person plural present tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It links the subject to the predicative adjective that follows.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here as the subject of the sentence and denotes a formal address towards the person being spoken to.</div><div><strong>erkältet</strong> This is a past participle of the verb "erkälten", which means "to catch a cold" in English. In this sentence, it is used as an adjective meaning "having a cold" or "suffering from a cold". It describes the possible state of the subject.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht wirst du bald hinfallen.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "perhaps" or "maybe". It indicates that there is a possibility that something might happen.</div><div><strong>wirst</strong> This is the second-person singular future tense of the verb "werden", which means "to become". In this context, it helps form the future tense and can be translated as "will". It suggests an action that might take place.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>bald</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "soon". It indicates that the action is expected to happen in the near future.</div><div><strong>hinfallen</strong> This is an intransitive verb that means "to fall down". It depicts the action that the subject might perform.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht werden wir heute Abend einen Film ansehen.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "maybe" or "perhaps". It indicates uncertainty or possibility.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is the future tense auxiliary verb in German, equivalent to "will" in English. It’s used to form the future tense.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>heute Abend</strong> This phrase combines "heute" (meaning "today") and "Abend" (meaning "evening") to indicate "this evening" or "tonight".</div><div><strong>einen Film</strong> This phrase contains the indefinite article "einen" (masculine accusative singular form of "ein") and the noun "Film" (meaning "movie" or "film"), forming "a movie" in English.</div><div><strong>ansehen</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German. "Ansehen" means "to watch" or "to view" in English. In the sentence, it is in its infinitive form placed at the end, as is typical in German sentence structure when using modal verbs or auxiliaries like "werden".</div>','<h2>Vielleicht war das nicht die richtige Antwort.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "perhaps" or "maybe". It suggests a possibility or uncertainty regarding the following statement.</div><div><strong>war</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "sein", which means "to be" in English. It indicates the state of being in the past.</div><div><strong>das</strong> This is the demonstrative pronoun "that" in English, used here as the neuter nominative singular to refer to "the answer".</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "not". It is used to negate a statement or concept.</div><div><strong>die</strong> This is the definite article "the" in English, used here in the feminine nominative singular form to precede "right answer".</div><div><strong>richtige</strong> This is the German adjective for "right" or "correct" in the feminine nominative singular form, matching "Antwort" in gender and case.</div><div><strong>Antwort</strong> This is the German noun for "answer" in the nominative case. It is feminine and thus takes the corresponding form of the definite article and adjective.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht werden sie die Partie gewinnen!</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb for "perhaps" or "maybe". It indicates the possibility or probability of an event occurring.</div><div><strong>werden</strong> This is a modal verb in German that is used to form the future tense, or to express probability. It is conjugated here as "werden" for the third-person plural, equivalent to "will" in English.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person plural personal pronoun in German, equivalent to "they" in English. It serves as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>die Partie</strong> This is a feminine noun in German meaning "the game" or "the match". "Die" is the definite article for feminine nouns in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>gewinnen</strong> This is the main verb in the sentence, meaning "to win". In this sentence, it’s an infinitive used together with the modal verb "werden" to form the future tense.</div>','<h2>Er hat auch sehr viel Talent.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It indicates possession or a characteristic of the subject.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It is used to add information to the sentence, indicating that the possession of talent is in addition to other characteristics or facts previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>sehr</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "very". It is used to intensify the adjective that follows it.</div><div><strong>viel</strong> This is a German adjective or adverb meaning "much" or "a lot". When used with an uncountable noun like "Talent", it means "a lot of".</div><div><strong>Talent</strong> This is a German noun meaning "talent". It is neuter and used here in the singular form to indicate a natural aptitude or skill.</div>','<h2>Sie läuft auch oft im Park.</h2><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the German personal pronoun for "she" in the nominative case. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>läuft</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "laufen", which means "to run" or "to walk". Here, it indicates the action the subject is performing.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It is used here to add information to the action, indicating that the subject performs the action in addition or in similarity to other actions or subjects.</div><div><strong>oft</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "often". It gives information about the frequency of the action.</div><div><strong>im Park</strong> This is a prepositional phrase. "Im" is the contraction of "in dem", where "in" is the preposition meaning "in", and "dem" is the definite article in the dative case for masculine/neuter nouns. "Park" is a German masculine noun meaning "park". The phrase translates to "in the park" in English, and it indicates the location where the action takes place.</div>','<h2>Ich liebe dich auch!</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It is the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>liebe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "lieben", which means "to love". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>dich</strong> This is the second-person singular accusative pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used here to indicate the direct object of the verb "lieben", the person who is being loved.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s an adverb used to add to what has previously been said, indicating that the speaker reciprocates the feeling or action.</div>','<h2>Ich mag Rock "n" Roll, aber ich mag Jazz auch.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of both clauses in the sentence.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen", which means "to like". It expresses a preference or liking for something.</div><div><strong>Rock "n" Roll</strong> This is a proper noun, taken directly from English, referring to a style of popular music that originated in the 1950s.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction in German that means "but". It’s used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> Again, this is the first-person singular pronoun in German, referring to the same person as the subject of the first clause and used again as the subject of the second clause.</div><div><strong>mag</strong> Once again, this is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "mögen". Here, it’s used for the second time to indicate another preference of the subject.</div><div><strong>Jazz</strong> This is another proper noun, referring to a genre of music that originated in the African-American communities of New Orleans, United States, in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is an adverb that means "also" or "too" in English. It’s used here to add another preference similar to the first one mentioned.</div>','<h2>Ich ziehe es vor, ein bisschen Zucker in meinem Kaffee zu haben.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>ziehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "ziehen", which means "to pull" or "to prefer" when used as part of the expression "etwas vorziehen" (to prefer something). In this context, it contributes to the phrase "ich ziehe es vor", which means "I prefer".</div><div><strong>es</strong> This is a neutral pronoun in German, equivalent to "it" in English. It is used here as a part of the expression "ich ziehe es vor".</div><div><strong>vor</strong> This is a preposition that means "before" or "in front of" in English. When combined with "ziehen" and "es", it is part of the expression "es vorziehen", which means "to prefer".</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It introduces the phrase "ein bisschen Zucker", which means "a little sugar".</div><div><strong>bisschen</strong> This word means "little" or "a bit" in English. It specifies the quantity and is used here to describe a small amount of sugar.</div><div><strong>Zucker</strong> This means "sugar" in English. It’s a noun and the object of preference in this sentence.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition that indicates location, equivalent to "in" in English. It introduces the phrase "in meinem Kaffee", which means "in my coffee".</div><div><strong>meinem</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, equivalent to "my" in English. It indicates that the coffee belongs to the speaker.</div><div><strong>Kaffee</strong> This means "coffee" in English. It’s a noun and indicates the beverage in which the speaker prefers to have sugar.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> This is an infinitive marker used before a verb, equivalent to "to" in English. It introduces the infinitive "haben", which follows next.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "to have" in English. It is used here to express the desire or preference of having something, which in this case is a bit of sugar in the speaker’s coffee.</div>','<h2>Er streicht ein bisschen Butter auf das Brot.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the German third-person singular pronoun meaning "he". It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>streicht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "streichen", which means "to spread". In this context, it indicates the action that he is doing.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This phrase translates to "a little" or "a bit" in English. It’s used here to describe the quantity of butter.</div><div><strong>Butter</strong> This is a German noun meaning "butter". It’s the object being spread by the subject.</div><div><strong>auf</strong> This is a German preposition meaning "on" in this context. It indicates where the butter is being spread.</div><div><strong>das Brot</strong> This phrase translates to "the bread" in English. "Das" is the definite article for neuter nouns, and "Brot" is the noun meaning "bread". Together they indicate the surface onto which the butter is spread.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte bitte ein bisschen Orangensaft haben.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the modal verb "möchten", which means "would like". It expresses a polite desire or preference.</div><div><strong>bitte</strong> This word translates to "please" in English. It is a polite form used to make a request more courteous.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This phrase means "a little bit" or "some", indicating a small quantity or amount.</div><div><strong>Orangensaft</strong> This is a compound noun in German meaning "orange juice". In German, compound nouns are joined to form a single word.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it serves to form a polite request together with the modal verb "möchte".</div>','<h2>Ich mache eine Reise mit ein paar Freunden.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>mache</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "machen", which means "to do" or "to make". In this context, it means "am making" or "do make" as part of a phrase describing an action being taken by the subject.</div><div><strong>eine Reise</strong> This phrase consists of an indefinite article "eine" (meaning "a" or "an" in English) and the noun "Reise", which means "trip" or "journey". Together, they mean "a trip" or "a journey".</div><div><strong>mit</strong> This is a preposition in German that translates to "with" in English. It’s used here to describe an association or accompaniment.</div><div><strong>ein paar Freunden</strong> This phrase consists of an indefinite pronoun "ein paar", meaning "a few" or "some" in English, and the noun "Freunden", which is the dative plural form of "Freund", meaning "friends". The entire phrase means "with a few friends". Note that "Freunden" in the dative case shows that it is used after the preposition "mit".</div>','<h2>Es gibt ein paar Pferde im Feld.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the neutral pronoun "it" in German, often used in impersonal constructions. Here, it serves as the grammatical subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give" or "there is/are" when used in an existential context, as it is here.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This phrase means "a few" or "a couple of" in English, indicating a small number or quantity.</div><div><strong>Pferde</strong> This is the plural form of "Pferd", which means "horse" in English. The noun is in the accusative case because it is the direct object of the verb "gibt".</div><div><strong>im</strong> This is a contraction of "in dem", which translates to "in the" in English. "In" is a preposition, and "dem" is the dative article for the neutral noun "Feld", indicating the location where the horses are.</div><div><strong>Feld</strong> This is a neutral noun meaning "field" in English. It describes the location of the horses and is in the dative case following the preposition "im".</div>','<h2>Es gibt ein paar Autos auf dem Parkplatz.</h2><div><strong>Es gibt</strong> This is a common expression in German which translates to "there is" or "there are" in English. It’s used to state the existence of something.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This translates to "a few" or "some" in English. It’s a quantifier that indicates a small number or amount of something.</div><div><strong>Autos</strong> This is the plural form of "Auto", which means "car" in English. Thus, "Autos" translates to "cars".</div><div><strong>auf dem</strong> This is a prepositional phrase that combines "auf" (on) and "dem" (the), which is the dative singular form of "der" (the) used after "auf" when it implies a location. So, "auf dem" translates to "on the" in English.</div><div><strong>Parkplatz</strong> This is a compound noun in German which translates to "parking lot" in English. It is made up of "Park" (park) and "Platz" (place/space), together designating an area designated for parking vehicles.</div>'];var defBonus = ['<h2>Nur ein schönes Shirt und vielleicht einen Blazer.</h2><div><strong>Nur</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "only" or "just". It limits the scope of what is being talked about to the items that are subsequently listed.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the German indefinite article for a masculine or neuter noun in the nominative or accusative case, corresponding to the English word "a".</div><div><strong>schönes</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "beautiful" or "nice". It precedes the noun "Shirt" and agrees with it in case, number, and gender. In this instance, it is in the accusative case due to the indefinite article "ein" preceding a neuter noun.</div><div><strong>Shirt</strong> This is a German noun (neuter) borrowed from English, meaning "shirt". It is the direct object in this sentence, referring to a piece of clothing.</div><div><strong>und</strong> This word is a German conjunction meaning "and". It is used to connect the words or phrases in the sentence.</div><div><strong>vielleicht</strong> This is a German adverb that means "perhaps" or "maybe", indicating that there is uncertainty or possibility regarding the second item of clothing.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the German indefinite article in the accusative case for masculine nouns, and it translates to "a" or "an" in English.</div><div><strong>Blazer</strong> This is a German noun (masculine) meaning "blazer". It is used here in the accusative case as the possible second item of clothing referenced in the sentence.</div>','<h2>Vielleicht musst du aufhören, auf Englisch zu denken.</h2><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is the German adverb meaning "perhaps" or "maybe". It indicates that the following statement is a possibility rather than a certainty.</div><div><strong>musst</strong> This is the second-person singular present tense form of the modal verb "müssen", which means "must" or "to have to". It expresses an obligation or necessity.</div><div><strong>du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>aufhören</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German and means "to stop" or "to cease". In the infinitive form here, it is linked with "zu" to form an infinitive phrase that is the object of the modal verb "musst".</div><div><strong>auf</strong> When used with "hören" as in "aufhören", this German preposition contributes to the meaning "to stop". However, it can also function as a normal preposition, meaning "on", "upon", or "at".</div><div><strong>Englisch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "English". It refers to the English language. In this sentence, it is in the accusative case as the object of the preposition "auf". Note that in German, nouns are always capitalized.</div><div><strong>zu</strong> In this context, "zu" is used to form an infinitive phrase together with "aufhören", creating the meaning "to stop". It is similar to the English to-infinitive, like in "to think".</div><div><strong>denken</strong> This is the German verb meaning "to think". Here, it’s in infinitive form and is part of the infinitive phrase "auf Englisch zu denken", which means "to think in English".</div>','<h2>Ich weiß nicht, vielleicht eine ehrenamtliche Tätigkeit.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>weiß</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "wissen", which means "to know" in English. It indicates the speaker’s state of knowledge or awareness.</div><div><strong>nicht</strong> This is the German word for "not". It negates the statement, indicating a lack of certainty or knowledge in this case.</div><div><strong>vielleicht</strong> This word translates to "perhaps" or "maybe" in English. It expresses uncertainty or the possibility of something.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is the feminine singular indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes a noun and matches the gender and case of the noun that follows, which in this sentence is "ehrenamtliche Tätigkeit".</div><div><strong>ehrenamtliche</strong> This is an adjective that means "voluntary" or "honorary" in English. It describes the type of activity referenced in the sentence.</div><div><strong>Tätigkeit</strong> This is a feminine singular noun in German, meaning "activity" or "occupation" in English. In the context of this sentence, it refers to some type of voluntary work.</div>','<h2>Ich verstehe. Vielleicht möchten Sie Loafers? Etwas weniger formell.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>verstehe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "verstehen", which means "to understand". It indicates that the subject comprehends or grasps the situation.</div><div><strong>Vielleicht</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "maybe" or "perhaps". It introduces a suggestion or a possibility.</div><div><strong>möchten</strong> This is the modal verb "mögen" in the subjunctive II form, and it corresponds to "would like" in English. It is used to express a polite desire or preference.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It’s used here to address someone in a polite or formal manner.</div><div><strong>Loafers?</strong> This word is adopted from English into German. "Loafers" are a type of slip-on shoes, and the term is used the same way in German as it is in English.</div><div><strong>Etwas</strong> This translates to "something" in English. It is used here to modify the degree of formality being discussed.</div><div><strong>weniger</strong> This comparative form of "wenig" in German means "less". It’s being used to compare the formality level of loafers to other types of shoes.</div><div><strong>formell</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "formal". When combined with "weniger", it suggests an alternative that is less formal.</div>','<h2>Nur eins, aber ich habe auch Handgepäck.</h2><div><strong>Nur</strong> This is the German word for "only" or "just". It is used to limit or specify the extent of something.</div><div><strong>eins</strong> This is the numeral "one" in German. It is used here to indicate a singular number or amount.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is the German word for "but". It’s a conjunction used to introduce a contrast or exception.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It shows possession, ownership, or the existence of something.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This means "also" or "too" in English. It’s an adverb used to include an additional piece of information.</div><div><strong>Handgepäck</strong> This compound noun means "hand luggage" or "carry-on baggage" in English. It refers to the luggage a passenger can carry onboard with them, typically in the cabin of an airplane.</div>','<h2>Ja. Ich möchte auch gerne einen Fernseher.</h2><div><strong>Ja</strong> This is the German word for "yes". It’s used to agree with a statement or answer positively to a question.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This comes from the verb "möchten", which is a modal verb similar to "would like" in English. In this sentence, it indicates a polite desire or wish.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It is used to add an additional point that is similar to one previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This German adverb translates to "gladly" or "willingly". It emphasizes that the speaker would be pleased to have what they are asking for.</div><div><strong>einen</strong> This is the accusative case of the indefinite article for masculine nouns, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It precedes a masculine noun which is the direct object of the sentence.</div><div><strong>Fernseher</strong> This is a masculine gender noun in German meaning "television". In the sentence, it’s the object that the speaker would like to have.</div>','<h2>Ich werde auch die Rouladen nehmen, ohne Senf.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>werde</strong> This is the first-person singular future tense auxiliary of the verb "werden", which is used to form the future tense in German. It suggests that the speaker is going to do something.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s an adverb used to include an additional action or item.</div><div><strong>die Rouladen</strong> This is the plural form of "die Roulade", which refers to "roulades" in English. It is a type of dish usually made of meat rolled around a filling.</div><div><strong>nehmen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "nehmen", which means "to take" in English. It’s used here with the auxiliary "werde" to form the future tense, indicating what the speaker will take.</div><div><strong>ohne</strong> This word means "without" in English. It’s a preposition used to indicate the absence of something.</div><div><strong>Senf</strong> This means "mustard" in English. It specifies the condiment that the speaker does not want included with their roulades.</div>','<h2>Und Sie müssen auch vermeiden, Alkohol zu trinken.</h2><div><strong>Und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It is a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal German personal pronoun for "you" in the nominative case. It can be used for both singular and plural, and it’s used here as the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>müssen</strong> This is the modal verb "must" or "have to" in English. It indicates necessity or obligation and is in the second-person plural form to match the formal "Sie".</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This translates to "also" in English. It is an adverb used to add information that is supplementary to what has been previously stated.</div><div><strong>vermeiden,</strong> This is the German verb "to avoid" in the infinitive form.</div><div><strong>Alkohol</strong> This is the German word for "alcohol". It is a noun in the accusative case as it is the direct object of the verb "vermeiden".</div><div><strong>zu trinken</strong> This is the infinitive construction "to drink" in English, with "zu" being the infinitive marker in German. This construction is used to express the action that should be avoided.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte auch, dass wir eine Blutprobe entnehmen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This word comes from the verb "möchten", which is a form of the modal verb "mögen" used to express politeness or a wish. In this case, it means "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is the German adverb for "also" or "as well". It is used to include oneself along with others or to add another statement.</div><div><strong>dass</strong> This is a conjunction in German that introduces a subordinate clause, meaning "that" in English. It indicates what the subject wants.</div><div><strong>wir</strong> This is a first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the subordinate clause.</div><div><strong>eine</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" in English. In this case, it is feminine accusative, preceding a female noun in the accusative case.</div><div><strong>Blutprobe</strong> This is a compound noun in German, meaning "blood sample" in English. "Blut" means "blood" and "Probe" means "sample" or "test".</div><div><strong>entnehmen</strong> This is a separable prefix verb in German which means "to take" or "to withdraw". In this sentence, the speaker expresses the desire to take a blood sample.</div>','<h2>Er hat auch dieses kleine Gästebadezimmer hier gebaut.</h2><div><strong>Er</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "he" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>hat</strong> This is the auxiliary verb for the perfect tense in German, from the verb "haben", which means "to have". In this sentence, it is used with the past participle to form the perfect tense, indicating a completed action.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It is an adverb used to add information to the sentence, indicating that the action is in addition to something else implied or previously mentioned.</div><div><strong>dieses</strong> This is the demonstrative pronoun in the neuter nominative/accusative singular form, meaning "this" in English. It is used here to specify which bathroom is being referred to.</div><div><strong>kleine</strong> This is an adjective in the neuter nominative/accusative singular form, meaning "small" in English. It describes the size of the bathroom.</div><div><strong>Gästebadezimmer</strong> This is a compound noun in German, where "Gäste" means "guest(s)" and "Badezimmer" means "bathroom". Together, they form "guest bathroom" in English. It’s in the nominative singular because it is the object of the sentence which was built.</div><div><strong>hier</strong> This adverb means "here" in English. It is used to indicate the location of the guest bathroom.</div><div><strong>gebaut</strong> This is the past participle of the verb "bauen", which means "to build" in English. In this perfect tense construction, it is used together with the auxiliary verb "hat" to indicate the completion of the action.</div>','<h2>Toll! Ich möchte auch dorthin fahren.</h2><div><strong>Toll!</strong> This is a German exclamation meaning "Great!" or "Fantastic!" It’s used to show enthusiasm or excitement about something.</div><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular form of the modal verb "möchten", which means "would like to". It expresses a desire or preference.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This word translates to "also" or "too" in English. It’s an adverb used to add information that is similar to or in agreement with the already mentioned.</div><div><strong>dorthin</strong> This is a combination of "dort" meaning "there" and "hin" indicating direction towards a place. Together, "dorthin" means "to that place" or "there" in terms of direction.</div><div><strong>fahren</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb "fahren", which means "to drive", "to travel", or "to go" (by vehicle). In this sentence, it’s used in conjunction with "möchte" to express the desire to go to a specified place.</div>','<h2>Danke! Du auch. Bis später Jochen!</h2><div><strong>Danke</strong> This is the German word for "thanks" or "thank you". It’s used to express gratitude.</div><div><strong>Du</strong> This is the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is used to address one person in an informal context.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is the German word for "also" or "too". Here, it’s used to reciprocate good wishes, similar to saying "you too" in English.</div><div><strong>Bis</strong> This is a German preposition that means "until". It’s commonly used to indicate the time until which an action is to be postponed.</div><div><strong>später</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "later". Combined with "Bis", it signifies "see you later" or "until later".</div><div><strong>Jochen</strong> This is a male given name in German. It is the equivalent of "Joe" or "Joachim" in English. In the sentence, it is a direct address to the person named Jochen.</div>','<h2>Ich auch. Sprechen Sie Deutsch in den USA?</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German word meaning "also" or "too". It indicates that the speaker is including themselves in the statement or agreeing with a previous statement.</div><div><strong>Sprechen</strong> This is the plural or formal form of the verb "to speak" in German, used here in the infinitive form.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal "you" in German. It is used to address someone respectfully or in a more formal context and can refer to both singular and plural forms.</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This term refers to the German language.</div><div><strong>in</strong> This is a preposition in German that can be translated to "in" in English. It’s used to indicate location or place.</div><div><strong>den</strong> This is the definite article for masculine plural nouns in the accusative case. It is used before "USA" to denote a specific country or place.</div><div><strong>USA?</strong> This is an abbreviation for "United States of America" and is used here to refer to the country where the person is asking if someone speaks German.</div>','<h2>Die Postkarte auch?</h2><div><strong>Die</strong> This is the German definite article for the feminine nominative case, equivalent to "the" in English. It’s used here to refer to a specific noun that is assumed to be known to the listener or reader.</div><div><strong>Postkarte</strong> This is a feminine noun in German, meaning "postcard". In this sentence, it is the main subject.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It indicates the inclusion of an additional item or confirmation of something just mentioned.</div>','<h2>Und Sie benutzen auch Zahnseide?</h2><div><strong>Und</strong> This is the German word for "and". It’s a conjunction used to connect words, phrases, or clauses.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> In this context, this is the formal second-person singular or plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "you" in English. It is capitalized to show formality and can refer to one person or several people in formal situations.</div><div><strong>benutzen</strong> This is the third-person plural or formal second-person singular present tense form of the verb "benutzen", which means "to use".</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "too". It indicates that the action or state applies additionally to what has been mentioned before.</div><div><strong>Zahnseide</strong> This is the German noun for "dental floss". It’s a compound noun with "Zahn" meaning "tooth" and "Seide" meaning "silk", though in this context, it refers to floss regardless of the material.</div>','<h2>Leeren Sie bitte auch Ihre Taschen.</h2><div><strong>Leeren</strong> This is a German verb meaning "to empty" or "to clear out". It is in the imperative mood and formal form (Sie), giving an instruction or order to the listener.</div><div><strong>Sie</strong> This is the formal German pronoun for "you" when addressing someone respectfully or in a formal situation. In the imperative form, it is placed after the verb.</div><div><strong>bitte</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "please". It is used here to make the request polite.</div><div><strong>auch</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "also" or "as well". It suggests that in addition to whatever else has been said or implied, the listener should also empty their pockets.</div><div><strong>Ihre</strong> This is the formal possessive pronoun in German, equating to "your" in English. It implies the possession of the pockets by the listener being addressed formally.</div><div><strong>Taschen</strong> This is the German word for "pockets", which is the direct object of the verb "leeren" in this sentence. The pockets are what should be emptied.</div>','<h2>Ich spreche ein bisschen Deutsch.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>spreche</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "sprechen", which means "to speak". It indicates the action being performed by the subject.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This phrase translates to "a little bit" in English. It is used here to indicate the speaker’s level of language proficiency.</div><div><strong>Deutsch</strong> This is a German noun meaning "German". It refers to the German language, and in this sentence, it is the direct object, the language that is being spoken to a limited extent.</div>','<h2>Gib uns ein bisschen mehr Zeit.</h2><div><strong>Gib</strong> This is the imperative form of "geben", which means "to give". It is used here as a command or request in the second-person singular.</div><div><strong>uns</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "us" in English. It is the indirect object of the verb "gib" and denotes the people to whom something is given.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" in English. It precedes the noun phrase "bisschen mehr Zeit".</div><div><strong>bisschen</strong> This is a diminutive form of "Biss", which means "bite". However, when used in this context, "ein bisschen" translates to "a little" or "a bit", indicating a small amount of something.</div><div><strong>mehr</strong> This is the comparative form of "viel", meaning "much" or "many". In this sentence, "mehr" functions as "more", creating a phrase that means "a little more time".</div><div><strong>Zeit</strong> This is a noun meaning "time" in English. It is the direct object of the sentence, referring to the time being requested.</div>','<h2>Es geht mir heute ein bisschen besser.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the third-person singular neuter pronoun in German, similar to "it" in English. It is often used in impersonal constructions.</div><div><strong>geht</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". In this context, it doesn’t literally mean "to go" but is part of the expression "Es geht mir ...", which translates to "I am feeling ...".</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This is the dative form of "ich", which is the first-person singular pronoun "I" in German. The dative case is used here to indicate the indirect object, which, in this phrase, is the person who is experiencing the feeling.</div><div><strong>heute</strong> This is an adverb meaning "today". It indicates when the action or state is taking place.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This phrase means "a little" or "somewhat". It is used here to modify the extent to which the subject is feeling better.</div><div><strong>besser</strong> This is the comparative form of the adjective "gut", meaning "good". In this context, "besser" means "better". It indicates that the speaker’s state or condition has improved compared to before.</div>','<h2>Wenn ich glücklich wäre, würde ich ein bisschen lächeln.</h2><div><strong>Wenn</strong> This is a German conjunction meaning "if". It introduces a conditional clause, expressing a hypothesis or condition.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the conditional clause.</div><div><strong>glücklich</strong> This is a German adjective meaning "happy". In this conditional clause, it describes the hypothetical state of the subject.</div><div><strong>wäre</strong> This is the first-person singular form in the subjunctive mood of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". Here it denotes a hypothetical or unreal condition in the past, as part of the condition clause.</div><div><strong>würde</strong> This is the conditional form of the auxiliary verb "werden" in German. It is used to form the conditional mood, which is equivalent to the English "would" in this context.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is repeated as the first-person singular pronoun in German, used here as the subject of the result clause that follows the condition.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This phrase means "a little" or "a bit" in English. It is used here to modify the extent of the action that follows.</div><div><strong>lächeln</strong> This is the infinitive form of the German verb "to smile". In this sentence, it’s used as the main verb in the result clause following the conditional form "würde".</div>','<h2>Oh! Okay, dann möchte ich gerne ein bisschen mehr Reis.</h2><div><strong>Oh!</strong> This is an interjection expressing surprise, realization, or acknowledgement, similar to its use in English.</div><div><strong>Okay</strong> This word is borrowed from English, indicating acceptance or agreement.</div><div><strong>dann</strong> This is a German adverb that means "then" or "in that case", indicating a consequence or a next step in a sequence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular of the modal verb "mögen" in its Konjunktiv II form, expressing a polite desire or wish, equivalent to "would like" in English.</div><div><strong>ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>gerne</strong> This is an adverb that means "gladly" or "with pleasure", expressing that the action is welcomed or desired.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is the indefinite article for masculine or neuter nouns in the accusative case, equivalent to "a" (or "an") in English.</div><div><strong>bisschen</strong> This is a neutral diminutive form of "Biss", meaning "a little" or "a bit". It makes the quantity more indefinite or smaller.</div><div><strong>mehr</strong> This is the comparative form of "viel", meaning "more". It indicates an increase in quantity or degree.</div><div><strong>Reis</strong> This is a German noun meaning "rice" in English. It is masculine and here it is in the accusative case, as it is the direct object of the sentence.</div>','<h2>Okay. Das ist ein bisschen früh, aber das ist mir recht.</h2><div><strong>Okay</strong> This is a German interjection similar to the English "okay", often used to express agreement or acknowledge something. </div><div><strong>Das</strong> This is a neuter singular article or demonstrative pronoun in German, usually translated to "the" or "that" in English. In this sentence, it refers to a situation or matter being discussed.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the German verb "sein", which means "to be". It connects the subject to a predicative expression.</div><div><strong>ein</strong> This is an indefinite article in German, equivalent to "a" or "an" in English. It’s used here before a masculine or neuter noun in the nominative case.</div><div><strong>bisschen</strong> This word means "a bit" or "a little" in English. It serves to slightly downplay or minimize what follows next.</div><div><strong>früh</strong> This is an adjective that means "early" in English. Here, it qualifies the time or event being referred to.</div><div><strong>aber</strong> This is a conjunction meaning "but" in English. It introduces a contrast or exception to the previous statement.</div><div><strong>das</strong> Here, "das" is again used as a neuter singular article or demonstrative pronoun, translated to "that" in English and referring back to the situation or matter being discussed.</div><div><strong>ist</strong> As before, this is the verb "to be" in the third-person singular present tense, used here to continue describing the situation.</div><div><strong>mir</strong> This pronoun means "to me" or "for me" in English, indicating that the following aspect of the sentence pertains to the speaker.</div><div><strong>recht</strong> This word can mean "right" or "proper" in English. However, in this context, the phrase "das ist mir recht" translates to "that is fine with me" or "that suits me".</div>','<h2>Nach ein bisschen Lesen ging sie ins Bett.</h2><div><strong>Nach</strong> This is a German preposition that means "after" in English. It is usually used to indicate a sequence in time or an occurrence following another event.</div><div><strong>ein bisschen</strong> This is a German phrase that means "a little" or "a bit" in English. It is used here to indicate a small amount of an activity.</div><div><strong>Lesen</strong> This is the German noun for "reading". It is derived from the verb "lesen", which means "to read". The word is capitalized because all nouns are capitalized in German.</div><div><strong>ging</strong> This is the third-person singular past tense form of the verb "gehen", which means "to go". In this sentence, it indicates that the action of going somewhere has taken place in the past.</div><div><strong>sie</strong> This is the third-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "she" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence and refers to a female.</div><div><strong>ins</strong> This is a contraction of the preposition "in" (meaning "to" or "into") and the definite article "das" (meaning "the"), combining into "ins", which is used with neuter nouns when referring to movement towards a place. It often translates to "into the" in English.</div><div><strong>Bett</strong> This is the German noun for "bed". Like in English, it can refer to both the physical object as well as the concept of going to sleep.</div>','<h2>Ich habe nur ein paar Dollar übrig.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>habe</strong> This is the first-person singular present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have" in English. It describes the action or possession related to the subject.</div><div><strong>nur</strong> This is a German adverb meaning "only" or "just". It limits or specifies the extent of something.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This phrase means "a few" in English and indicates a small, unspecified quantity of something.</div><div><strong>Dollar</strong> This is the same as in English, referring to the currency "dollars". In German, nouns are always capitalized.</div><div><strong>übrig</strong> This is an adjective that means "left over" or "remaining" in English. It describes the state of something that exists after everything else has been subtracted or used up.</div>','<h2>Ihnen fehlen ein paar Mitspielerinnen.</h2><div><strong>Ihnen</strong> This is the formal second-person pronoun in the dative case in German, equivalent to "to you" in English. It denotes to whom the action is related.</div><div><strong>fehlen</strong> This is the third-person plural present tense form of the verb "fehlen", which means "to lack" or "to be missing". Here the verb is used to indicate that something is absent or missing to someone (as the indirect object reflected by "Ihnen").</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This is a phrase that translates to "a few" in English. It’s used before a noun to express an indefinite, small quantity.</div><div><strong>Mitspielerinnen</strong> This is a compound noun, which comes from "Mitspieler" meaning "teammates" or "players", with the feminine plural suffix "-innen" added to mean "female teammates" or "female players".</div>','<h2>Es gibt ein paar Docks entlang des Flusses.</h2><div><strong>Es</strong> This is the German pronoun for "it". Here, it acts as a dummy subject, similar to the impersonal "there is" construction in English.</div><div><strong>gibt</strong> This is the third-person singular present tense form of the verb "geben", which means "to give". In this context, it works together with "es" to mean "there is" or "there are", indicating the existence or presence of something.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This is a phrase meaning "a few" or "some" in English. It implies a small number or quantity.</div><div><strong>Docks</strong> This is the German word for "docks", taken directly from English. It is the plural form and refers to platforms for loading, unloading, and mooring boats or ships.</div><div><strong>entlang</strong> This is a German preposition or adverb that means "along" in English. It indicates orientation along a path or line.</div><div><strong>des Flusses</strong> This is a genitive case construction combining the definite article "des" (of the; masculine/neuter, singular) with "Fluss" (river), which means "of the river" in English, signifying possession or relation to the river.</div>','<h2>Ich möchte dir ein paar Fragen stellen.</h2><div><strong>Ich</strong> This is the first-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "I" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>möchte</strong> This is the first-person singular conjugation of the modal verb "möchten", which expresses a polite desire, wish, or preference. It’s a conditional form of "mögen" and can be translated as "would like to".</div><div><strong>dir</strong> This is the dative form of the second-person singular pronoun in German, equivalent to "to you" in English. It indicates the indirect object of the sentence, the person to whom the questions will be posed.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This phrase translates to "a few" in English. It’s used here to specify a small number of items—in this case, questions.</div><div><strong>Fragen</strong> This is the plural form of the German noun "Frage", which means "question". It’s the direct object of the verb "stellen".</div><div><strong>stellen</strong> This is the infinitive form of the verb that means "to put/place/set" in English. When used with "Fragen", it means "to ask" as in "to pose questions". In this sentence, "stellen" works with the modal verb "möchte" to express a polite intention to ask questions.</div>','<h2>Wir haben ein paar Minuten vor unserer Mittagspause.</h2><div><strong>Wir</strong> This is the first-person plural pronoun in German, equivalent to "we" in English. It’s the subject of the sentence.</div><div><strong>haben</strong> This is the first-person plural present tense form of the verb "haben", which means "to have". It is used here to express possession or in this case to indicate a period of time they have.</div><div><strong>ein paar</strong> This is a phrase meaning "a few" or "a couple of". It quantifies the noun that follows.</div><div><strong>Minuten</strong> This is the plural form of the noun "Minute", which is the same in English – it means "minutes". It is the direct object of the verb "haben", indicating what they have a few of.</div><div><strong>vor</strong> This is a preposition that can have various meanings depending on context, in this case, it means "before". It introduces the time frame being referred to.</div><div><strong>unserer</strong> This is a possessive pronoun in the dative case, feminine singular form, meaning "our". It precedes "Mittagspause" to show possession.</div><div><strong>Mittagspause</strong> This compound noun consists of "Mittag", which means "noon", and "Pause", which means "break". Together, they mean "lunch break". It is the object of the preposition "vor", indicating the time before which they have a few minutes.</div>'];definitions = definitions.concat(defBonus);